latestPosts.caption:
Introducing Shirt V3 - it’s actually strange how important a product this is in hindsight. In 2023 we put out a raw hem shirt and thought nothing of it. It did so well that for the first time in GARUDA’s history we thought “should we make it an other colour?”… Even if it doesn’t have the raw hem anymore, it still offers a one of a kind fit block that others may try but simply cannot replicate. That shoulder to armhole to chest to length ratio comes from 7 years of operating a made to measure brand, and having an excel sheet of over 300 peoples measurements to find the ideal fit from. 

That eye catching strap you saw your favourite fashionista flaunting a few years ago? it was just flashy with the added utility of allowing you to sling your shirt cross body so you didn’t have to tie it around your waist like a school kid. Then we gave the option of making it removable in V2, but that was an either or solution. Through months of constant wear testing, we found a solution that allows internal and external rigging. Don’t want the extra attention the strap brings? Still want the utility of the cross body sling? Just rig the sling internally. 

It’s funny how the smallest changes can increase usability, adding a flap to the pocket protects any precious items, but making the flap half an inch smaller than the pocket? Perfect for a gap for your pen. Others may forget but we also secure the pen in place with a hidden bar tack stitch under the flap to stop the pen from sliding around. Thats more thought applied to a 2x2 inch section of a garment than you may see in an entire product these days. 

Finishing off with something old, and something new. The V2 variant of the shirt introduced the hem expansion plackets on the hem. Allowing you to increase volume, drape, flow, and achieve the neatest half tucks you’ve ever seen (wouldn’t be us if it didn’t have utility). This feature has been carried forward and full credit for it belongs to Assistant Designer Jayant. Whats new? The fabric. Don’t worry it’s still 100% cotton, but it is naturally dyed now. The onion colour is dyed with madder, and the iron… well with iron.

latestPosts.caption:
Final test shoot and fittings for “heirlooms” the ‘24 collection. 
I basically decided to let my mind wander freely with no concern over deadlines, the calendar, or sell-ability. For years we have been terrible at marketing, and as a result been on a hamster wheel of releasing products; using drop frequency as a marketing tool, which is a skill in itself but also exhausting. We kinda got less terrible at marketing this year and biker jackets be selling themselves homie. So the shackles are off 100% this time, even if this collection flops my dog Gary will be fed. 
Some of these things take over a week to make, and I’m relatively sure no one else would bother making them potentially because they are stupid or potentially because they are incredible and extremely difficult to make. 
As always I have no statement or story to tell, the garments are process focused and the products reflect the processes used to create them. That’s fancy design talk for “I made things”. 
- sincerely Suhail
